            ">Kashmir militants dead</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/kashmir-militants-neutralized-pahalgam-attack.jpg" alt="Indian soldiers patrol a road in Kashmir following a militant attack near Pahalgam, as the government claims to have neutralized the attackers and political opposition voices concern." href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>In April 2025, militants attacked tourists in Indian‑administered Kashmir, killing 26 civilians, which led to intensified tensions between India and Pakistan. Credits: Sanna Irshad Mattoo/Reuters</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> Indian officials confirmed that three Pakistani militants responsible for the Pahalgam attack <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-were-killed-in-a-joint-operation?source=website" target="_blank">were killed in a joint operation</a> in Dachigam National Park near Srinagar. The Indian Home Minister confirmed the three dead were Suleiman Shah, Afghan (both identified as members of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-lashkar-e-taliba?source=website" target="_blank">Lashkar-e-Taliba</a> terrorist group), and Jibran, and recovered one M9 American rifle and two AK-47s, which were used to attack the tourists. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The criticism:</strong> Opposition leaders criticized the government over security failures, questioning how the attackers crossed into India in one of the country’s most heavily militarized zones. They called for an inquiry into the apparent intelligence lapses and delays in finding the attackers. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The other perspective:</strong> Pakistan's state-run media claimed that <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-india-planted-a-fake-encounter?source=website" target="_blank">India planted a fake encounter</a> targeting Pakistani nationals. Pakistan has long accused India of staging gun battles in Kashmir and killing Indian prisoners in fake gunfights while posing them as combatants. Many Kashmiri Muslims support the terrorists’ goal of uniting the territory with Pakistan or becoming an independent country. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Know more about the history of the Kashmir conflict <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-here?source=website" target="_blank">here</a> (video).  
          </p>
