        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Iceland’s EU candidacy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: Iceland may reopen EU accession talks by 2027, but opposition is still strong.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The what:</strong> Iceland could re-enter discussions to join the European Union, with the government proposing a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-referendum-by-2027?source=website" target="_blank">referendum by 2027</a> on whether to resume formal accession talks. The country first applied for EU membership in 2009 and had opened 27 out of the 33 accession chapters before talks were suspended in 2013. While not an EU country, Iceland participates in the European Economic Area (EEA), aligning with many EU policies.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The factors:</strong> Iceland’s renewed interest is caused by changing geopolitical conditions, including security in the Arctic, tensions between the US and EU, Russia’s war in Ukraine, and the rising Chinese influence. EU officials have signaled openness to Iceland’s return, offering better trade ties and a defense partnership. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         However, internal resistance remains high (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-see-our-write-up?source=website" target="_blank">see our write-up</a>), particularly from the rising fishing and farming industries, which fear EU regulations could compromise Iceland’s economic autonomy. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-a-recent-poll?source=website" target="_blank">A recent poll</a> shows that 58% of Iclanders support the idea of holding a referendum to restart the talks, but support for the EU membership is still lower, with 45% in favor. 
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The big picture:</strong> While EU enlargement efforts have mostly focused on Ukraine and the Western Balkans, Iceland stands out because it already meets many EU standards and could progress faster if public and political support align. Its admission would send a strong signal that the EU remains attractive even to stable, wealthy democracies, especially after Brexit.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
