        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>Wallerstein believed that modernization theory and similar models stemmed from nineteenth-century thinking that compartmentalized knowledge.</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px 0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The introduction:</strong> World-systems theory (created by American sociologist Immanuel Wallerstein in the 1970s) explains global inequality through the lens of capitalist expansion. It argues that the world is a single, interconnected economic system where some countries benefit at the expense of others.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The concept:</strong> The theory divides countries into three categories:
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-table font-family="Roboto+Serif" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="0px 18px 0px 18px" style="width: 100%">
          <tr>
            <td style="
                font-size: 18px;
                width: 20px;
                vertical-align: top;
                padding-right: 8px;
                line-height: 1.6;
              "> → </td>
            <td style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6"> 
           <strong>Core countries</strong> are wealthy, industrialized nations that control the global economy, advanced technology, and hold political power.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="
                font-size: 18px;
                width: 20px;
                vertical-align: top;
                padding-right: 8px;
                line-height: 1.6;
              "> → </td>
            <td style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; line-height: 1.6">
          <strong>Peripheral countries</strong> are less developed, often dependent on exporting raw materials or underpaid labor, and are economically exploited by the core.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="
                font-size: 18px;
                width: 20px;
                vertical-align: top;
                padding-right: 8px;
                line-height: 1.6;
              "> → </td>
            <td style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; line-height: 1.6">
           <strong>Semi-peripheral countries</strong> are situated between the two; they are more developed than the peripheral, but still subordinate to the core.</td>
          </tr>
        </mj-table>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         This hierarchy explains how wealth and power are distributed.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      <strong>The example:</strong> In the smartphone industry, the US (core) handles design, branding, and earnings. China (semi-peripheral) manufactures and assembles the smartphones, and Congo (peripheral) delivers raw materials like cobalt, often under exploitative conditions.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      <strong>The critique:</strong> Critics argue that this theory has a Eurocentric approach, that it <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-jul-25-foundations-h1-14-downplays-local-factors?source=website" target="_blank">downplays local factors</a> like governance, and oversimplifies the complex realities. Still, it remains influential as it highlights that the imbalance in global wealth and power is systemic, not accidental.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
